---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

const schema = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "AI Coding Assistants Compared: Copilot vs Cursor vs Cody vs Continue vs Codeium",
    "description": "A comprehensive comparison of the top AI coding assistants in 2026 to help you choose the best tool for your workflow.",
    "author": {
      "@type": "Organization",
      "name": "siliconbased.dev"
    }
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Is Cursor better than GitHub Copilot?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "For many developers, yes. Because Cursor is a fork of VS Code, it integrates AI at the editor level rather than just as an extension. This allows it to read your entire codebase and make multi-file edits more effectively than Copilot."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Are there any free AI coding assistants?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes. Codeium offers a very generous free tier that rivals Copilot in autocomplete performance. Continue.dev is open-source and allows you to plug in your own local or API-based LLMs."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Is my code safe with these AI tools?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "It depends on the tool and tier. Enterprise tiers of Copilot and Cursor guarantee they won't train on your code. Open-source tools like Continue allow you to run models locally, guaranteeing 100% privacy."
        }
      }
    ]
  }
];
---

<SiteLayout
  site="siliconbased"
  title="AI Coding Assistants Compared: Copilot vs Cursor"
  description="A comprehensive comparison of the top AI coding assistants in 2026 to help you choose the best tool for your workflow."
  canonical="https://siliconbased.dev/github-copilot-guide"
  schema={schema}
>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>AI Coding Assistants Compared</h1>
      <p>Copilot, Cursor, Cody, Continue, and Codeium head-to-head</p>
    </div>

    <div class="back-link-container">
      <a href="/top-developer-tools-2026" class="back-link">← Back to Top 20 Developer Tools</a>
    </div>

    <section class="article-body">
      <h2>The New Normal of Development</h2>
      <p>AI coding assistants are no longer a novelty; they are a fundamental part of the modern developer stack. However, the landscape has fragmented into extension-based tools and AI-native editors.</p>

      <h3>1. GitHub Copilot: The Industry Standard</h3>
      <p>The tool that started the revolution is still the most widely adopted in enterprise environments.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Architecture:</strong> An extension that lives inside your existing editor (VS Code, IntelliJ, etc.).</li>
        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> Deep integration with GitHub, excellent enterprise security/compliance, universally supported across almost all IDEs.</li>
        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> Can struggle with whole-project context compared to AI-native editors.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="card related-card">
        <h3>Optimizing Copilot in VS Code</h3>
        <p>If you're using Copilot, you're likely using VS Code. Make sure your editor is fully optimized by reading our <a href="/vscode-deep-dive">VS Code Deep Dive guide</a>.</p>
      </div>

      <h3>2. Cursor: The AI-Native IDE</h3>
      <p>Cursor took a different approach: instead of building an extension, they forked VS Code and built AI directly into the core.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Architecture:</strong> A standalone application (forked from VS Code).</li>
        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> "Composer" feature allows for complex, multi-file edits. Unmatched ability to index and understand your entire codebase. You can use your existing VS Code extensions.</li>
        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> Requires you to switch from your vanilla VS Code installation.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>3. Codeium: The Free Contender</h3>
      <p>Codeium proves you don't need to pay $10-$20 a month for high-quality autocomplete.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Architecture:</strong> Extension-based.</li>
        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> Lightning-fast autocomplete, an incredibly generous free tier for individuals, and proprietary models fine-tuned specifically for code.</li>
        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> Chat features sometimes lag behind the GPT-4/Claude integrations found in paid competitors.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>4. Continue.dev: The Open-Source Choice</h3>
      <p>Continue brings the "bring your own model" (BYOM) philosophy to the coding assistant space.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Architecture:</strong> Open-source extension for VS Code and JetBrains.</li>
        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> Ultimate flexibility. You can plug in local models (via Ollama) for total privacy, or provide your own API keys for GPT-4, Claude, or Gemini.</li>
        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> Requires more setup and configuration than plug-and-play alternatives.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>5. Sourcegraph Cody: The Enterprise Context King</h3>
      <p>Cody leverages Sourcegraph's powerful code search technology to provide AI with superior context.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Architecture:</strong> Extension-based.</li>
        <li><strong>Strengths:</strong> Phenomenal at answering questions about massive, monolithic enterprise codebases that span multiple repositories.</li>
        <li><strong>Weaknesses:</strong> Overkill for small personal projects.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="card related-card">
        <h3>AI in the Terminal</h3>
        <p>AI isn't just in your editor anymore. Terminals like Warp now have AI built directly into the command line. <a href="/terminal-tools-compared">See our terminal comparison</a>.</p>
      </div>

    </section>
  </div>

  <script is:inline>
    // Interactivity
  </script>

  <style is:inline>
    .page-content { max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 2rem 1.5rem; }
    .hero { text-align: center; padding: 3rem 0 2rem; }
    .hero h1 { font-size: 2.2rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .hero p { color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 1.1rem; }

    .back-link-container { margin-bottom: 2rem; }
    .back-link { color: var(--accent-color); text-decoration: none; font-weight: 600; }
    .back-link:hover { text-decoration: underline; }

    .article-body { font-size: 1.1rem; line-height: 1.6; color: var(--text-primary); }
    .article-body h2 { margin-top: 2.5rem; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color); padding-bottom: 0.5rem; color: var(--accent-color); }
    .article-body h3 { margin-top: 2rem; }
    .article-body p { margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
    .article-body ul { margin-bottom: 1.5rem; padding-left: 1.5rem; }
    .article-body li { margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }

    .card { background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem; margin: 1.5rem 0; }

    .related-card { background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent-color) 5%, var(--card-bg)); border-left: 4px solid var(--accent-color); }
    .related-card h3 { margin-top: 0; font-size: 1.2rem; }
    .related-card p { margin-bottom: 0; }
    .related-card a { color: var(--accent-color); text-decoration: none; font-weight: 600; }
    .related-card a:hover { text-decoration: underline; }
  </style>
</SiteLayout>
